Financial metrics temporarily unavailable (rate limited) - 2025-09-18

Title   : Private banks, NBFCs and defence stocks to lead market gains: Rahul Shah 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-18T07:12:04
Fetched : 2025-09-18T13:37:43.408563
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/private-banks-nbfcs-and-defence-stocks-to-lead-market-gains-rahul-shah/articleshow/123967643.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
“The way the markets have been, the domestic macro factors have been very-very strong,” Shah noted. He pointed to robust inflation data, higher GST collections, a supportive monsoon, strong auto sales, and ample liquidity from the RBI as building blocks for the rally. Despite global volatility, he said, largecap leaders have outperformed, with “old economy stocks showing very-very strong performance in the last two quarters.”
Banking remains his top pick. “Private banks like HDFC and ICICI are expected to see 20% growth from FY26 to FY28. Both have robust balance sheets, strong return ratios, and healthy credit growth,” he said. On the PSU side, State Bank of India stands out. “All three banks—HDFC, ICICI, and SBI—have outperformed in the last six-eight months, and we believe they will continue to do well.”
Shah also sees opportunity in NBFCs and HFCs. “Shriram Finance and L&T Finance will continue to do well. The cost of borrowing will go down, benefiting balance sheets and P&L immediately. Valuations are reasonable and risk-reward is favourable.”
On manufacturing and electronics, Shah highlighted Dixon Technologies. “People might debate valuations, but with stellar guidance of 40% growth from FY26 to FY28, they look justified. Any correction is a buying opportunity,” he said.
Defence stocks, though volatile, remain on his radar. “Bharat Dynamics has corrected 15% from highs, making valuations attractive. BEL continues to be a strong performer. Small allocation to Mazagon Dock also makes sense,” Shah suggested.
Overall, financials, electronics, and select defence names remain in focus as investors look beyond short-term volatility toward structural growth themes.
(Disclaimer: Recommendations, suggestions, views and opinions given by the experts are their own. These do not represent the views of The Economic Times)
