Title   : Apollo Hospitals reports completion of over 51 lakh surgeries, 27,000 organ transplants as it marks 42 years
Source  : www.thehindubusinessline.com
Published: 2025-09-18T11:19:52
Fetched : 2025-09-18T13:43:22.437514
URL     : https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/apollo-hospitals-reports-completion-of-over-51-lakh-surgeries-27000-organ-transplants-as-it-marks-42-years/article70065214.ece
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Apollo Hospitals on Thursday commemorated its 42nd anniversary. The healthcare major said it has completed over 51 lakh surgeries and 27,000 organ transplants through the four decades and touched over 200 million lives.
Apollo has also trained over 11 lakh professionals, significantly augmenting the skilled healthcare human capital in the country.
“Our vision has always been to make world-class care accessible and future-ready. As India rises on the global stage, Apollo will remain a driving force, shaping healthier societies, advancing medical frontiers and ensuring that families everywhere can look to the future with hope, health and happiness,” Dr Prathap C Reddy, Chairman, Apollo Hospitals Group said.
By reducing dependency on foreign care, raising clinical benchmarks across sectors and expanding access to millions, Apollo has directly contributed to longer lives, stronger survival rates and India’s reputation as a trusted global healthcare destination, the company said in a statement.
“From preventive care to advanced treatments, from digital health to research, every expansion has been built on trust, access and impact. As India stands at the cusp of becoming a $5 trillion economy, healthcare must be its strongest foundation,” Dr Suneeta Reddy, Managing Director, Apollo Hospitals Group, said.
Among its various firsts, Apollo counts initiatives such as South Asia’s first Proton Cancer Centre, India’s first AI-Precision Oncology Centre and the region’s first CyberKnife Robotic Radiosurgery system.
Dr Sangita Reddy, Joint Managing Director – Apollo Hospitals added, “At Apollo, we are integrating AI, robotics and digital platforms to not just treat disease, but to predict and prevent it. Imagine a world where every Indian has a digital health twin, where interventions are precise, affordable and accessible in real time—that is the future we are building.”
Dr Prathap Reddy opened the first hospital in Chennai in 1983. Today, Apollo is the world’s largest integrated healthcare platform with over 10,400 beds across 79 hospitals, 6,800+ pharmacies, 2,900+ clinics and 500+ telemedicine centres.
