Title   : Dev Accelerator shares hit 5% lower circuit, back at IPO price. What should you do? 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-18T07:54:22
Fetched : 2025-09-18T13:51:18.060262
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/dev-accelerator-shares-hit-5-lower-circuit-back-at-ipo-price-what-should-you-do/articleshow/123968910.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Rs 143-crore IPO, priced in the Rs 56–61 range, attracted healthy investor interest during the bidding process. However, the grey market premium (GMP) remained subdued ahead of yesterday’s listing.
What should investors do?
Valuations appear rich, with the stock trading at 310x P/E, making it one of the top 16 costliest stocks in the country. Sunny Agrawal of SBI Securities has taken a ‘Neutral’ view, recommending that investors track the company’s performance post-listing before taking fresh positions. He advises against any FOMO-driven approach.
“The company's modest profit margins and high debt levels warrant caution. Risk-tolerant investors can hold for the medium to long term with a stop-loss of Rs 50 per share,” said Shivani Nyati, Head of Wealth at Swastika Investmart Ltd. “The company aims to capitalize on the growing demand for flexible office spaces, catering to startups, SMEs, and large enterprises seeking scalable office solutions,” she added.
Anand Rathi, on the other hand, recommends that investors hold the stock for the long term, noting that the company has broadened its offerings to include HR, IT, and software services through Saasjoy, strengthening client retention and addressing evolving workplace and technology needs. Additionally, through its associate Scaleax Advisory Private Limited, it helps GCCs build global teams in India by providing facility and payroll management, as well as recruitment solutions such as talent sourcing, AI-based screening, and team augmentation.
The company has shown strong revenue momentum, with topline growth from Rs 69.9 crore in FY23 to Rs 158.9 crore in FY25, registering a CAGR of over 50%. EBITDA margins remain healthy at above 50%, though PAT is modest at Rs 1.8 crore in FY25.
High lease liabilities and interest costs continue to weigh on net earnings. Post-issue, the company's debt-to-equity ratio is expected to ease from 2.4x to around 1x, aided by IPO proceeds earmarked for debt repayment and fit-outs at proposed centres.
