Title   : Stronger, deeper, broader: Market cap of listed firms up 4.5x in 10 years under Modi, says BSE CEO 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-18T06:37:21
Fetched : 2025-09-18T15:09:57.994982
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/stronger-deeper-broader-market-cap-of-listed-firms-up-4-5x-in-10-years-under-modi-says-bse-ceo/articleshow/123966679.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Speaking to ET Now on the Prime Minister’s birthday, Ramamurthy said the Indian market has become “deeper, broader, and more stable” over the past 10 years.
“The market capitalization of BSE-listed companies has grown 4.5 times during this period. Demat accounts have increased tenfold, mutual fund portfolios have expanded eight times, and assets under management (AUM) have risen six times,” he said.
Ramamurthy added that smaller towns and cities are increasingly participating in the markets. “The share of B30 cities in the market has almost doubled in the last decade, and SIP investments have also surged significantly,” he noted. Despite global uncertainties, he said India has delivered an average annual market return of 13%, reflecting the country’s resilience and growth momentum.
Highlighting PM Modi’s reform agenda, Ramamurthy credited key initiatives such as Jan Dhan Yojana, Aadhaar, Ayushman Bharat, Atmanirbhar Bharat, the Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code, GST reforms, asset monetisation, and labour reforms for boosting growth.
“These reforms have not only transformed financial markets but also strengthened India’s economy. GDP has more than doubled, startups have flourished, and capital formation has accelerated,” he said.
Ramamurthy also pointed to the rapid growth of UPI transactions, which now surpass the GDP of several large countries, as evidence of India’s digital transformation.
He concluded by stressing that India has shown maturity and resilience in managing global shocks, including the COVID-19 pandemic. “India continues to be the fastest-growing major economy in the world,” he said.
