Financial metrics temporarily unavailable (rate limited) - 2025-09-18

Title   : Maruti Suzuki cuts prices of its cars by up to 24% 
Source  : www.thehindubusinessline.com
Published: 2025-09-18T10:04:12
Fetched : 2025-09-18T15:15:43.111058
URL     : https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/maruti-suzuki-cuts-prices-on-its-cars-by-up-to-24/article70065061.ece
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Country’s largest passenger vehicles (PVs) maker Maruti Suzuki India (MSIL) on Thursday said it will reduce the prices of all it products, over and above the GST reduction, starting from September 22 till December 31.
For the entry-level cars, the company has reduced the price of S-Presso by ₹1.29 lakh and the Alto K10 by ₹1.07 lakh. For Celerio, the price has been reduced by ₹94,100; WagonR by up to ₹79,600 and Ignis by up to ₹71,300, MSIL said.
On entry segment like S-Presso, the reduction beyond GST is in the range of 12.6 per cent to 24 per cent, for Alto K10, it is in the range is 10.6 per cent to 20 per cent and for Celerio, the range is 8.6 to 17 per cent. For its most popular compact car, WagonR, MSIL has reduced the prices by 8.7 to 14 per cent.
Price of premium hatchback Swift is reduced by up to ₹84,600; Baleno by up to ₹86,100; Tour S by up to ₹67,200; Dzire by up to ₹87,700; Fronx by up to ₹1,12,600; Brezza by up to ₹1,12,700; Grand Vitara by up to ₹1.07 lakh; Jimny by up to ₹51,900; Ertiga by up to ₹46,400 and XL6 by up to up to ₹52,000, the company added.
This is a double bonanza for festive season to accelerate motorisation in the country, in regards to the entry-level small cars, but for other vehicles across categories, the company has also reduced the prices beyond GST rate cut, Partho Banerjee, Senior Executive Officer - Sales and Marketing, MSIL told reporters.
“Maruti Suzuki, being the market leader thought that it is time now to come with some offerings that would upgrade the two-wheeler customers to four-wheeler...There can’t be any better time than to really go for the motorisation in the Indian market. And, as the car penetration in India is so low, at 34 per 1,000 people, it makes it all the more compelling...we are taking this initiative to put India on wheels,” Banerjee said.
Earlier, there were three challenges: high car prices due to implementation of emission and other regulatory norms; due to high prices, down payments increased which was challenge for affordability; high EMI was also another hurdle for such customers, he added.
Published on September 18, 2025

